@government
go-to: menu

The European Republic is a semi-presidential republic, with a parliament, simply known as the European Parliament or simply the Parliament and a president with some executive power.

The European Parliament is elected based on a proportional representation system, giving parties seats roughly proportional to their vote share in each member state. The president then appoints the prime minister and the cabinet, who are responsible for government. A majority vote of no-confidence in the parliament can remove the current government.

The President is elected by a national direct vote, in two rounds. The second round is used if the first round does not result in a majority for one candidate, being between the two top candidates of the first round, with the one winning a majority becoming president. The role of the president is mostly to represent Europe, but they also have some crucial governing powers. The president appoints and can remove the prime minister, and can thus influence the formation of a government. They also hold control over the European military.

Europe is divided into a number of member states, each of which have their own governments with large responsibilities. The largest member states include Germany, France, Italy, Spain and Poland.

@weimar_timeline
go-to: menu

= Timeline of the European Union and later Republic of Europe from 2024 to 2036

**2024**: The European parliamentary elections see a crushing defeat for the euro-sceptic right, previously having been expected to make major gains. The incumbent grand coalition easily retains a majority.

**2025**: The EU pushes through the largest yet aid program to Ukraine, with more Russia-friendly leaders begrudgingly accepting it as they see their own poll numbers decline due to the rise of pro-Ukraine sentiment. This, together with the largest yet American aid package, organised by President Harris, begins to turn the war in Ukraine's favour.

**2027**: Facing a collapsing economy and slow but steady Ukrainian gains, President Putin of Russia is forced to sign the Treaty of Minsk, surrendering all territory held in Ukraine except Crimea. Ukraine is allowed to join the EU, but is forbidden from joining NATO. Pro-federalism sentiment is increased substantially.

**2028**: The EU passes a resolution calling for a long-term process to federalise the union, not without massive opposition from the euro-sceptic parts of both the right and left. Ukraine is finally admitted into the union as well.

**2029**: The 2029 european parlaiment elections see yet another crushing defeat for the Eurosceptic parties as a lot of parties campaign for officially moving forward with federalisation. However, the process remains slow.

**2030**: The european parlaiment begins the first step towards federalisation, passing a bill to unify the electoral process for the parlaiment across the entire union, with the previous blocks becoming parties, and national parties no longer being on the ballot in the european elections. To allow this to be implemented, a snap election is called.

**2031**: The snap election is held. The election is very polarised between pro-federalisation and anti-federalisation parties, with the parties not taking a clear side doing poorly. The pro-federalisation side wins decisively and progress towards federalisation continues, but is slow.

**2032**: The United Kingdom rejoins the union after 63% of the voters vote to rejoin in the referendum launched by Prime Minister Starmer under preasure from his coalition partners in the liberal democrats.

**2033**: The EU votes to have a referendum on federalisation. 68% of voters vote to federalise the union, as the commission makes federalisation its number one goal. Negotiations are slow.

**2034**: The final resistant national leaders to federalisation fold, as it is becoming increasingly obvious that it cannot be resisted anymore. However, negotiations remain slow as different nations support different ways for the federation to work.

**2035**: The commission publishes its proposed constitution. The two most controversial parts are creating a European presidency and removing the right to secession. The commission refuses to compromise on either point.

**2036**: The constitution barely passes. The new European Republic is a reality.

